B. WiFi Mesh Network
To extend the network coverage, we formed an ad-hoc mesh Wi-Fi network using BATMAN -adv on the border router, i.e., Raspberry Pi 3B. The internet access will be shared across all the nodes. To analyze the effect of number of hops on internet speed, we setup an experiment as shown in Fig. 7. which consists of four primary functional blocks, Raspberry Pi 3B node running B.A.T.M.A.N adv, router, Internet connection and a PC to conÔ¨Ågure each node using SSH. The Ad-hoc mesh of nodes is formed by Raspberry PI 3B nodes. The Ad-hoc Wi-Fi mesh is conÔ¨Ågured by installing batman-adv 2018 version for raspberry by OpenMesh. Node in network 1 is connected to internet via ethernet by the router. Nodes in network 2 and 3 do not have access to internet and are connected to a PC, to conÔ¨Ågure and log data via SSH. Similarly, Node 1 is managed by a PC in network 1. All the three nodes are conÔ¨Ågured to use on board Broadcom BCM43438 wireless wlan0 interface to participate in the Ad-hoc Wi-Fi mesh.

